    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-01-11T09:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-01-11T09:40:00-05:00" n="221"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d221">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.51/1190.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Sullivan</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Santo Domingo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-11T10:00:00-04:40">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 11, 1914, 10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Dominican Government desires to pledge alcohol tax, an internal revenue, to
                    secure from Royal Bank of Canada $30,000 loan for three <pb facs="0312" n="196"
                        xml:id="pg_196"/> months. The bank wants my approval. Government claims it
                    must fall unless current expenses are met. The advanced $20,000 authorized by
                    you from customs give Government only ninety-five hundred dollars by Dominican
                    Minister’s blunder in depositing same in national bank “to credit” of the
                    Dominican Republic. No question of Government’s financial difficulty. I believe
                    that now is the time to demand reforms. Government never so reasonable.
                    Constitutional Convention meets next week. We will endeavor to insert habeas
                    corpus. Please suggest further reforms that Department may desire in organic
                    law. Telegraph instructions as to the loan not later than Monday. No funds for
                    Tuesday’s needs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sullivan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
